<P><FONT size=3 face="Arial Black">H.M. Dockyard Rosyth - The Original Easton Gibb &amp; Son Bound Claim Book for the Construction of the Monoliths.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT size=3 face="Arial Black">About 452pp (including two illustration diagrams), detailing the claim for £131,023 which the contractor Easton Gibb &amp; Son had against The Admiralty for their loss in carrying out the work at Rosyth. The contractors maintained that the specification supplied by the Admiralty were badly thought out and occasionally incorrect, resulting in additional work in sinking the foundations and wells in the monoliths. Undated, though c.1920-22. Two illustrations showing cross sections of the monoliths.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT size=3 face="Arial Black">Approx. 255x370mm., water damage to the lower right corners of the first 40 pages, resulting in some loss and affecting some text and both illustrations. The damage also affects the covers, with some loss to the front.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT size=3 face="Arial Black">Easton Gibb &amp; Son built the tidal basin and three graving docks at Rosyth between 1909 and 1916. By 1911-12 Guy Maunsell had been promoted to sub-agent, in charge of the block-making yard and the monolithic foundations to the outer wall of the dockyard. Later, and until his departure from the company in 1914, he was chief sub-agent and staff manager responsible for outside operations. The project encompassed land reclamation behind a sea wall, docks, a power station and a pumping station, plus workshops and stores. The 485 ha site had a 4km long water frontage, and up to 6,000 men worked there. Friction arose between client and contractor, the Admiralty believing its own plans for implementing the project could not be bettered, while Sir Alexander Gibb disagreed, with Maunsell submitting a number of alternatives. The dispute lasted three years and final settlement was not reached until 1922. </FONT></P></SPAN></FONT><!-- Begin: Sellathon V3.0 -->
