<p>&nbsp;</p><p style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="font-size: x-large;">Manchukuo. Imperial Visit to Japan Commemorative Medal in original fitted case of issue, 1935 <br /></span></strong></p><p style="text-align: center;">&nbsp;</p><p style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Oxidised silver medal in the form of a stylised spearhead, on  laterally-pierced cylinder suspension; the face decorated with orchid  and chrysanthemum blossoms, the Imperial flowers of Manchukuo and Japan,  a scroll imposed at the base inscribed &lsquo;I Te I Hsin&rsquo; (One in virtue and  in spirit), describing the union of Japan and Manchukuo (from the  Japanese perspective); the reverse inscribed with characters meaning  &lsquo;Kang Teh 2nd Year, Manchukuo Empire, Emperor&rsquo;s visit to Japan  Commemorative Medal, 4th Month, 6th Day&rsquo;; age-toned; on probably  replaced correct ribbon with hook and eye fittings; in rare original  pasteboard fitted case of issue with surface scuff and loose hinge. The  medal was instituted by Imperial Edict on 21 September 1935 to  commemorate the visit of the Manchukuo puppet emperor Pu Yi to Japan in  April 1935. Japan invaded Manchuria in 1931 and set up the &lsquo;Independent&rsquo;  State of Manchukuo. On 1 March 1934, Henry Pu Yi, last of the Manchu  Emperors of China, was proclaimed Emperor of Manchukuo and became  nominal head of government. The Soviet Red Army took the area in 1945  and it was occupied by the Chinese Communist People Liberation Army  shortly thereafter, being subsequently reincorporated into China. The  medal is now rare.</span></p><p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</p><p style="text-align: left;"><link rel="File-List" href="file:///C:%5CUsers%5Cnigel%5CAppData%5CLocal%5CTemp%5Cmsohtmlclip1%5C01%5Cclip_filelist.xml" /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
